The beans were not cooked, still semi-hard and there was so much of liquidly juice from the server not draining it properly before adding it to my bowl.  Of course the brown bags was soaked and juice was spilling out of the closed lid bowl.  And for some reason the food is not hot enough for the cheese to melt, and my bowl was take-out.  Returning to work 15 minutes later you would think the mozzarella cheese melted, NOT, as always.  Final complaint.  Using the number on my receipt, I tried to call the location, because I was not going back there to tell them that their beans weren’t cooked, but all I got was a website name.  PS The meal was filling but I'm done with this Harlem location.  I hope if try another location I will not experience the same bad service.

Okay, so it's a new location, and right now they seemed a bit disorganized.  That's okay, they'll learn as they go along.  Let's focus on what is working: - The place is super-clean, and all tables and chairs are sparkling new - The staff is friendly and helpful - The female manager has good people skills, and seems to care about the place - They have a security guard - The food is pretty fresh.  And they have the best cilantro-lime rice of any Chipotle location I've been to.  Here's what needs improvement: - They tend to run out of items and need to get more adept at preventing that - The line moves fairly slow, something to work on - They need to do like other Chipotles when people ask for guacamole, i.e. tell the person upfront that guac will be an extra $2.50  Hey, they'll get better.  For now, not a bad idea to be thankful that they're in Harlem now, as they're definitely one of the better chain restaurants.  I wish I had one in my neighborhood .
